  footnotes:
  - key: '[주-D001] 머리엔 …… 몸에는 봉액(縫腋) : '
    value: 공자가 송나라에 살 때에는 그 곳에서 쓰는 장보관(章甫冠)을 쓰고, 노(魯)나라에 살 때에는 봉액의(縫腋衣)를 입었다 하여 후세에서 유학(儒學)하는 이의 의관(衣冠)을 이것으로 말하였다.
  - key: '[주-D002] 띠[芧]가 …… 마주 당기네 : '
    value: 《주역》에 있는 말인데, 띠[芧] 뿌리를 뽑으면 한꺼번에 여러 뿌리와 줄기가 같이 뽑혀 올라온다는 뜻이니, 여기서는 모든 선비들이 한데 엉키어 공부한다는 말이다.
  - key: '[주-D003] 청자(靑紫) : '
    value: 벼슬하는 이의 큰 띠와 인끈이 푸른색 붉은색이란 말이다.
  - key: '[주-D004] 뒤집으면 …… 엎으면 비 : '
    value: 두보의 빈교행(貧交行)이란 시의, “손을 뒤집으면 구름을 만들고 엎으면 비를 만들어 분분하니, 어찌 헤아릴 수 있겠는가.”라는 구절에서 인용하였다.
  - key: '[주-D005] 강유(剛柔)를 …… 하나니 : '
    value: 《시경》에, “강(剛 여문 것)이라고 토해 내고, 부드러운 것이라고 삼키지 않는다.”는 귀절이 있는데, 여기서는 이해관계에 따라 떨어졌다 붙었다 하는데 인용한 것이다.
  - key: '[주-D006] 꽃다운 …… 은일 : '
    value: 은일(隱逸)로 살아간 도연명(陶淵明)이 국화를 매우 사랑하였고, 주무숙(周茂叔)의 애련설(愛蓮說)에, “국화는 꽃 중에 은일(隱逸)이다.” 하였다.
  - key: '[주-D007] 송대부(松大夫) : '
    value: 진시황(秦始皇)이 태산(泰山)에 올라 갔다가 창졸에 폭우를 만나 큰 소나무 밑에서 피하고 나서 그 소나무에 오대부(五大夫)의 벼슬을 봉해 주었다.
  - key: '[주-D008] 맑은 …… 물과 같으니 : '
    value: “소인의 교분은 단술과 같이 달고 군자의 교분은 물과 같이 담담[淡]하다.”는 옛글이 있는데 그것은 단술은 달콤하다가도 잘 변해지고 물은 담담하여도 변하지 않는다는 데 비유한 것이다.
  - key: '[주-D009] 남산을 바라보노라 : '
    value: 도연명(陶淵明)의 시에, “국화를 동쪽 울타리 아래에서 따라가는 유연히 남산을 보네[采菊東籬下 悠然見南山].” 이라는 구절이 이있다.
english:
  title: Ode to the Chamber of Chrysanthemum Friendship
  author: Kang Hee-maeng
  language: eng
  text: |-
    There is a great master whose belly holds the Five Classics,
    Whose mind encompasses the Six Arts.
    He has plumbed the mysteries of human nature and destiny,
    Analyzed the boundary between Heaven and Man.
    Wearing the formal cap of scholars with noble bearing,
    His sleeves flutter as he walks through the world.
    Through the gate of literature he gathers friends,
    Fragrances of orchid and iris bloom among the worthy of his age.
    When companions gather, their paths merge;
    Like reeds uprooted together, hearts intertwine.

    Entering the Hall of Sage Teaching,
    He sits in the Academy's great hall,
    Leading scholars through the sacred texts—
    His warm words drift like spring breezes,
    His stern words strike like winter frost.
    He exalts virtue over technique,
    Rejects the way of hegemons, honors the way of kings,
    Makes Yao and Shun the model of ruler and ruled,
    Restoring this age to the grandeur of ancient sage-kingdoms.

    Alas, you scholars striving in the way!
    Heaven has arranged the Five Relationships,
    Friendship holds its place among them.
    Through distance, strangers become intimate;
    Setting aside the gulf of years to honor the path,
    Transcending rank to befriend even ministers.
    In endless time with infinite people,
    Who does not require friendship to complete their virtue?

    Do you understand the nature of friendship?
    Though ten thousand forms of companionship exist,
    Do you know what constitutes true beneficial friendship?

    A student approaches, trailing his light belt and long robes,
    Walking with measured steps, neither hurried nor slow,
    Bowing three times as he advances, then pausing in humble retreat.
    Kneeling respectfully, he speaks:

    "My hearing and sight are dull and dim,
    My conduct clumsy and confused.
    Yet listening to your supreme teachings,
    It is as though the veil has been lifted from my eyes.

    I have heard that among humanity in this world,
    The kinds and numbers are infinitely many.
    Sorted by type, divided into groups,
    Each finding their own companions and friends.
    How can one exhaustively discuss them all?

    In friendship, there are roughly three kinds:

    The highest has no self-interest—
    In such friendship there is no barrier.
    Stripping away the superficial,
    Respect and trust intermingle.
    This is the friendship of moral virtue,
    Where the heart holds no shame.

    The middle seeks mutual aid—
    Whether in poverty or prosperity, one heart shared.
    Sweeping aside rank and reward together,
    Bonding with a strength no metal can break.
    This is the friendship of ambition and glory,
    Varying in depth and shallowness.

    The lowest is treacherous and false—
    Flip your hand, clouds appear; reverse it, rain falls.
    Weighting heavy when fortune smiles, light when it frowns,
    Swallowing what is hard, spitting out what is soft.
    This is the friendship of advantage and profit—
    What good does it finally bring?

    Surveying heaven and earth,
    Reflecting on ancient and modern times,
    Though friendship manifests in countless ways,
    It never exceeds these three categories.

    How is it, master, that you choose your friend
    In the chrysanthemum alone, scorning all others?"

    The master then turns his azure eyes and strokes his frost-white beard,
    Leans upon the armrest of ancient wood,
    Calls the student forward and instructs with eloquence:

    "The friendships of feeling and emotion
    Begin in union but end in separation.
    From youth, when hearts were perfectly matched,
    Bonds strong as gold and stone,
    Glued together more firmly than lacquer and glue,
    Trusted more than Chen and Lei,
    Compared with Guan and Bao's devotion—
    Swearing by Heaven and spirits never to change,
    Seeking to remain constant to the end without fault.

    Yet when fortune shifts, when rank and wealth diverge,
    Old bonds are forgotten,
    Comradeship once precious becomes a source of sorrow.

    Or perhaps a moment's slight,
    A glance awry, sets spears and halberds bristling in the breast.
    A sharp blade hidden beneath a smile,
    Until finally friends become destroyers,
    Promises turn to dust.

    Heart answered heart's pledge,
    Yet they end turning their backs, transformed.
    Friendship that changes becomes enmity.

    Thus do we know that human friendship
    Is indeed inferior to the heartless plant.

    Do you comprehend why this chrysanthemum
    Possesses such steadfast integrity,
    Such fragrant purity, such serene withdrawal from the world?

    When golden wind sweeps through,
    The sky turns crystalline blue,
    Heavy frost descends at dawn,
    Cold dew settles at dusk.
    All trees shed their leaves,
    A thousand mountains stand bare-ribbed.
    Swallows depart their nests, vanishing without trace,
    And raptors return to the forest, beating their wings.

    The garden lies swept and silent,
    Decaying grasses scattered in desolation.
    Even the plum's pure melody,
    Even the lotus's opened heart—
    All wither and fade away.
    How much more so the gaudy blooms and painted petals?

    I then lean upon my staff and wander,
    Seeking fragrant whispers among the remaining stems.
    Cold petals gleam like precious jewels,
    Dense leaves glow jade-green.

    Touched by thick frost, it grows more radiant,
    Basking in faint sunlight, more resplendent still.

    I pluck the golden blooms and brew them into wine;
    The fragrance swells as liquid droplets fall.
    Clusters of flowers drift upon the cup,
    That aromatic breath rises and rises.

    It opens the throat and cleanses the lungs,
    Fills the entire body with heavenly fragrance,
    Penetrates liver and bone,
    Until self and thing become one, both forgotten.

    In that moment, speech itself vanishes,
    And we drift together into the realm of intoxication."

    The student, hearing these words, trembles with joy,
    And continues with a song:

    "Spring, summer, autumn, winter—each flickers, each changes,
    All the flowers of spring and summer fade away.
    But you, chrysanthemum, bloom last, bloom first,
    Your pure fragrance pierces to the bone.

    Though ten thousand leagues of dust veil the eyes,
    Though bitter frost sweeps through the hair,
    You keep your fragrance whole and undiminished,
    Committing your quiet heart to the bright moon."

    Again the student addresses the master:
    "Frivolous friendship corrupts virtue,
    But true friendship is straightforward and upright.

    The stalwart pine has its integrity,
    The graceful bamboo has its composure,
    Yet lack the color and scent.
    So I take the chrysanthemum's lonely beauty as my friend,
    And make it my mirror for observing things and cultivating the self."

    The master smiles gently,
    Sighs deeply while leaning on his desk,
    Calls for wine and brush,
    Grasping the cup and wielding the ink.

    "Let our friendship be like clear water—
    Stainless, undying through the years.
    Walking through the eastern garden three times to breathe its fragrance,
    I gaze upon the southern mountains standing high."
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The Five Classics (五經) and Six Arts (六藝) refer to the foundational texts and skills of Confucian learning.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'Chapter Initiate's Cap' and 'Sewn-Seam Robe' reference Confucian scholars' traditional dress.
  - key: ''
    value: Chen and Lei, Guan and Bao are famous pairs of friends from Chinese antiquity, representing the highest ideals of friendship.
  - key: ''
    value: The three types of friendship—moral virtue, ambition and glory, and profit—are a traditional Confucian classification.
  - key: ''
    value: The chrysanthemum represents solitary virtue and hidden integrity, particularly through its association with the poet Tao Yuanming, who loved it.
  - key: ''
    value: The final reference to 'picking chrysanthemums at the eastern fence while gazing at the southern mountain' echoes Tao Yuanming's famous poem, suggesting the integration of philosophical friendship with natural observation.
